the splash page in the front

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:54.880
of the book, and you could read
that this story was written

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:56.270
by Chris Claremont
[assumed spelling],

00:05:56.270 --> 00:06:00.380
drawn by John Byrne,
inked by Terry Austin.

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:01.680
So that --

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:03.410
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: Good,
so good, so good.

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:07.740
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: That created the
idea that these things are not made

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:10.520
by an elaborate computer algorithm,

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:18.210
that actual human beings are behind
these works, and from day one,

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:23.580
I never wanted to be a policeman
or fireman or something like that.

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:27.550
It was always -- always
going to be comics for me.

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:29.150
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: So once you knew

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:32.610
that you would be a comic book
artist even as a young person,

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:36.570
like what trajectory, like did
you make a plan that you're

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:39.010 position:56%
like this is how I'm going to do it?

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:40.310
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah.

00:06:40.310 --> 00:06:44.610
The goal because I was very --
I had a lot of self-awareness,

00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:49.060
and I knew that my skills were
weak, I wasn't going to be one

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:53.790
of these outlier 14-year-old
cartoonists,

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:56.440
wonder kid genius types.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:01.450
So in a lot of those Marvel comics,
there would be an ad somewhere

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:04.380
in the middle for the
Joe Kubert School

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:08.010
of Comic Art and blah, blah, blah.

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:13.160
So that was my goal for my entire
childhood through high school

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:18.440
to just build a strong portfolio
that was good enough to be able

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:23.910
to gain entry into that
amazing institution.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:30.330 position:56%
I would read a lot of articles about
-- about the alumni of that school

00:07:30.330 --> 00:07:32.970 position:56%
and how tough it was to get in there

00:07:32.970 --> 00:07:36.290
and how you really
have to be on the ball.

00:07:36.290 --> 00:07:38.700
You can never be late
with an assignment

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.620
because they'll kick
you the hell out.

00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:42.680
And I was preparing
for all this stuff,

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:48.740 position:56%
putting together this big portfolio,
and I got in, and once I made it

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:50.790
to campus, I'm looking around me.

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:55.420
I was probably one of the younger
people to ever go to the school

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:59.100
because a lot of people would take
a couple years off and maybe go

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:03.220
to real university for
awhile or whatever.

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:06.050
But I quickly learned that you --

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:11.060
if you have the money to afford
to get in, they'll let you in.

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:12.400
So what I'm saying
is I was surrounded

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:15.300
by a lot of knuckle heads.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:17.930
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: But that
was your -- that was your --

00:08:17.930 --> 00:08:22.730
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: My young -- my young
childhood, before that point,

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:28.230
working up to that point I easily
made a thousand comic book pages

00:08:28.230 --> 00:08:30.390
that will never see
the light of day.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:31.730
So I have a bunch of them too.

00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:36.770
And it would vary from making my
own stories, which would be very,

00:08:36.770 --> 00:08:41.380 position:56%
very -- four or five page things
that were meant to be bigger comics,

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:45.350 position:56%
but after three pages, I would get
a better idea and just abandon that,

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:47.520
go do something else all the way

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:50.780
up to just copying,
complete comic books.

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:53.590
It's like I drew -- I
copied the first issue

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:55.900
