00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:15.190
I almost divorced my parents
like Dominique Moceanu,

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:20.080
the 1994 gymnast, gold medalist.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:21.890
I'm sorry.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:23.190
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: No.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:24.490
That's okay.

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:29.040
So about storytelling,
comic book storytelling.

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:30.340
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yes.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:31.640
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: Okay.

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:33.550
So now -- now we realize, as
I said, comic books age huge.

00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:35.680
The comic book world is huge.

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:41.570
Major motion pictures are -- every
year there's like ten of them.

00:09:41.570 --> 00:09:42.870
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Right.

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:46.210
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: What -- what
can comics do in storytelling

00:09:46.210 --> 00:09:49.970
that other formats can't do?

00:09:49.970 --> 00:09:53.390
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Well,
the marriage of words

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:57.320
and pictures is nothing
to sneeze at.

00:09:57.320 --> 00:10:01.540
The ability to go back a
couple of pages and kind

00:10:01.540 --> 00:10:06.110
of revisit somethings can
be a storytelling component.

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:10.350
You can draw something that
seemed incidental on one page.

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:16.040
It could have some payoff five
pages later that makes you go back

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:19.010
or upon second reading,
you're like, "Oh my goodness.

00:10:19.010 --> 00:10:21.040
This object was there
the whole time."

00:10:21.040 --> 00:10:25.240
There are -- there's -- I mean,

00:10:25.240 --> 00:10:27.980
we could talk about
that all day for sure.

00:10:27.980 --> 00:10:30.780
It's something I really like.

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:32.910
The idea that you're
seeing this whole unit

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:38.720 position:56%
at once is an interesting challenge
to overcome because as a cartoonist,

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:44.720
one of the big puzzles is trying
to capture the reader's attention

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:48.210
and also their motives
so it's like you want

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:51.010 position:56%
to lead their eye in a specific way.

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:54.060
And that's not easy to do.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:56.050
It has a lot of advantages.

00:10:56.050 --> 00:11:02.710 position:56%
Like I said, my entire life has been
devoted to the art of making comics.

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:06.750
But if we were to be
frank in our discussion,

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:10.120
it's a tremendously
inefficient form of storytelling

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:11.710
if we want to be honest about it.

00:11:11.710 --> 00:11:19.220
The amount of time put in to each
page and the yield that you receive

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:22.860
in terms of how long it
takes to read is very fast.

00:11:22.860 --> 00:11:32.050
But it's the coolest -- what I like
about it most is it's democratic.

00:11:32.050 --> 00:11:37.360
It's -- you just need a pencil
and paper to be able to do it.

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:39.690
You don't need a focus group.

00:11:39.690 --> 00:11:43.070
You don't need a lot of money
to put a comic together.

00:11:43.070 --> 00:11:44.820
So the budget can be endless.

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:46.980
You mentioned the Hollywood movies

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:52.340
that have these multi hundred
dollar budgets or whatever.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:56.050
To do -- to achieve the
same effect in a comic,

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:58.870
you just need the price
of pencil and paper.

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:00.170
&gt;&gt; Damon Locks: Right, right.

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:02.230
And people can enjoy it for like
-- well, it used to be 35 cents.

00:12:02.230 --> 00:12:04.060
Now it's like $3?

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:05.360
$4?

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:06.660
&gt;&gt; Ed Piskor: Yeah.

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:08.290
You remember the old
danger of comics

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:11.630
